'''Johnson "John" Juanda'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/poker/columns/story?columnist=bluff_magazine&id=2948473|title=Reading John Juanda|author=Danny Aller|date=2007-07-28|accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> (born July 8, 1971 in [[Medan]], [[Indonesia]])<ref>[http://www.worldpokertour.com/Shared/Players/Bios/J/Johnson_Juanda.aspx World Poker Tour profile]</ref> is an [[United States|American]] professional [[poker]] player based in [[Marina del Rey, California]].

Juanda lives in [[Los Angeles]]. He was born and raised in Indonesia but is [[Chinese Indonesian|ethnically Chinese]]. John arrived in the United States in 1990, when he enrolled at [[Oklahoma State University]]. He earned an [[MBA]] from [[Seattle University]].

John was a high school [[track and field|track]] star for the 200 meter [[Athletics sprints|sprints]] to 5000 meter [[Long distance track event|races]]. He had a stint as a door to door [[sales]]man selling [[Bible]]s.

In both 2001 and 2002 he was [[Cardplayer Magazine|Cardplayer Magazine's]] tournament Player of the Year, winning four [[World Series of Poker]] titles, and a World Poker Open Championship title.<ref>[http://www.cardplayer.com/magazine/article/14387 Cardplayer.com: Sometimes, Nice Guys Finish First]</ref> In November 2004 he won the inaugural [[Professional Poker Tour]] event at [[Foxwoods Casino]] in Connecticut.

In November 2005 he earned nearly $500,000 in [[Monte Carlo]], [[Monaco]] after winning the Monte Carlo Millions Consolation tournament, finishing sixth in the Monte Carlo Millions Main Event, and finishing second at "The FullTiltPoker.Net Invitational Live from Monte Carlo." 

In January 2006, Juanda defeated a field including [[Jeff Lisandro]], [[Mike Sexton]], [[Barry Greenstein]], [[Tony Bloom]], [[Tony G]] and [[Phil Ivey]] to win the [[Australian dollar|AUD]]1,000,000 ($732,901) first prize in the [[Crown Australian Poker Championship]] AUD100,000 [[speed poker]] event

Juanda won the 2008 [[World Series of Poker Europe]] <U+00A3>10,000 No Limit Holdem Main Event, earning <U+00A3>868,800 ($1,580,096). A little over a week later, he finished runner-up to [[Jason Mercier]] at the [[European Poker Tour]]'s London <U+00A3>1 Million Showdown, a non-title no limit holdem event also known as the <U+00A3>20,000 High Roller event, earning <U+00A3>327,000 ($598,770). 

Although Juanda has made 6 World Poker Tour final tables, he has never captured a title. He has finished 2nd (Bellagio Season 1), 3rd (WPT Invitational Season 2), 4th (Mirage Season 3), 5th (twice; Aruba Season 3 & Niagara Falls Season 5), and 6th (Bellagio Season 3) at the final tables he has appeared at. He has also finished 7th (PartyPoker Cruise Season 2) and 8th (Legends Season 5), just missing two more opportunities at another final table.

As of 2009, his total live tournament winnings exceed $9,300,000.<ref>[http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/player.php?a=r&n=130 Hendon Mob tournament results]</ref> Juanda's 45 cashes at the WSOP have been good for $3,195,087 of his live tournament winnings.<ref>[http://www.worldseriesofpoker.com/players/index.asp?sort=cashearned, World Series of Poker Earnings], www.worldseriesofpoker.com</ref>

Juanda is a member of "Team Full Tilt" at [[Full Tilt Poker]].<ref>[http://www.fulltiltpoker.com/johnJuanda.php Full Tilt Poker profile]</ref>

